    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Map Scale Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Enter the denominator of your map's scale ratio. For a map labeled 1:50,000 you would type 50000. Enter the distance you measured on the map and pick the unit you used (centimeters are most common on metric maps, inches on US maps). The calculator instantly returns the real-world distance that corresponds to what you measured, in meters, kilometers, miles, feet, and yards so you can use whichever unit suits the job. You can measure with a ruler, a piece of string laid along a curving trail, or the scale bar provided on the map itself.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>What a Scale Ratio Really Means</h2>
      <p>
        A scale ratio of 1:N means that one unit of length on the map corresponds to N units of the same length on the ground. So on a 1:25,000 map, 1 centimeter equals 25,000 centimeters, which is 250 meters, or a quarter of a kilometer. On a 1:100,000 map, 1 centimeter equals 1 kilometer. Memorizing a few common ratios saves time in the field: 1:25,000 → 1 cm = 250 m, 1:50,000 → 1 cm = 500 m, 1:100,000 → 1 cm = 1 km. Imperial maps follow the same rule: on a 1:24,000 USGS quad sheet, 1 inch equals 2000 feet, because 24,000 inches divided by 12 is 2000 feet.
      </p>

      <h2>Choosing the Right Scale</h2>
      <p>
        The right map scale depends entirely on the task. For hiking and orienteering, 1:10,000 to 1:25,000 gives enough detail to distinguish individual trails, boulders, and fences. For cycling and car touring, 1:50,000 to 1:250,000 strikes a good balance between coverage and legibility. For road trips and regional planning, 1:500,000 to 1:1,000,000 is more practical. For country- or continent-wide views, 1:5,000,000 and smaller is appropriate. Remember that larger-scale maps (smaller denominators) show less area in more detail, while smaller-scale maps (larger denominators) show more area with less detail.
      </p>

      <h2>Measuring Curvy Paths</h2>
      <p>
        When a trail, river, or road curves on a map, a straight ruler underestimates the true length. Use a flexible item such as a piece of string, lay it along the path, mark the end, and then measure the string with a ruler. Or use a map wheel (also called a curvimeter), a small tool with a wheel on the bottom that you roll along the line to accumulate distance. Either way, apply the scale ratio to convert the measured length to the real-world distance. For digital measurement, most GIS and outdoor apps provide a polyline measurement tool that computes the real distance along a drawn path automatically.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What does a scale like 1:50,000 mean?</h3>
      <p>One unit on the map equals 50,000 units in the real world. So 1 cm on the map is 500 m on the ground.</p>

      <h3>What's the difference between large and small scale?</h3>
      <p>A large-scale map has a small denominator and shows less area in more detail. A small-scale map has a large denominator and covers more area with less detail.</p>

      <h3>What are common map scales?</h3>
      <p>1:24,000 and 1:100,000 for USGS topographic maps. 1:25,000 and 1:50,000 for UK Ordnance Survey. 1:500,000 to 1:1,000,000 for road atlases.</p>

      <h3>How does scale relate to distortion?</h3>
      <p>On a globe, scale is constant. On a flat map the scale is only exactly accurate along the projection's central lines, and distortion grows outward.</p>

      <h3>Can I use this for digital maps?</h3>
      <p>Yes, if you know the effective scale of the display. Many digital maps show a scale bar you can measure with a ruler on the screen.</p>

